We probably need to forward errors to the caller in this case to let them know that they only got partial results.

Now.... how do we do that correctly?  IDK.  let me know if you need help interpreting the dead sea scrolls.... I mean the redfish standard.

> Now.... how do we do that correctly?
I'm not sure either.  If we get partial results then we'd still want to return a 200 with those results.  I've looked over the schema for the Chassis collection as an example (https://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/ChassisCollection.json).  It doesn't look like there's a field we can use to say that some items are likely missing.

There are also scenarios where the collection might not exist on a satellite, but we wouldn't normally expect it to anyway.  We could be searching for something like Fabrics which exists in the schema but is not currently supported in bmcweb.  Maybe some of the satellites support that resource collection. In that case I don't think it's noteworthy that the collection does not exist on the other satellites.

Since this is the initial check, what we can do is set asyncResp to return the received error as long as asyncResp was not already going to return a 200.  That way we wouldn't be clobbering the partial results.

I've made the change to do so.  I'll leave this open in case you have a better idea.
Done

Couple things here:

1. This is a possible nullptr dereference.  always check for validity.
2. This should be a helper function on the Response object.  Ideally with the same prototype as the Request object to be similar.
3. On most stl objects, operator[] creates a key if it doesn't exist, which isn't really what you intended here.  I forget if boost::beast::fields follows stl here, but I suspect it would.

As a safety check, we also need to check content-encoding.  in the context of this patch, feel free to just bail out if content-encoding is set to anything, but we don't want to accidentally parse a gzip payload as json, as it could give security vulnerabillities.

This same situation exists in the earlier router patch (https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/53310).  For now I'll use the same function call I created for that patch.  I'll come back to this an update it with the final version of what I use in that patch.
Done
Please don't do this fallback.  I understand why you did it, and I appreciate the thought, but its against the security standard, and encourages implementations to ignore putting in this field.
I removed the fallback and added a check at the end to notify the user if the response was not a json.
Also needs reported to the user somehow.

We can return an operationFailed message as long as it won't require overwriting what would be an otherwise valid response.  That would be the desired resource collection exists on the aggregating BMC or we were able to retrieve it from a satellite BMC.

I've made the change.
I feel like I shouldn't sort the array in an effort to keep all of the local resources together.

ideally sort before the array (generally sort on dbus path or something simpler).  Yes, technically, we don't have to sort per the standard, but in my experience, you shortcut a lot of submitted "bugs" by having some sort order that makes sense to humans (ironically, that's why the current function is called "human sort")

"local resources then aggregated resources" seems like a reasonable sort order to me, and relatively explainable.

where people tend to get touchy is when you get stuff like:

dimm1
dimm11
dimm12
dimm2
dimm20
dimm21

ect.


Also, per the standard, we need to return a consistent response, so the response order can't be based on the order that http calls return.

> "local resources then aggregated resources" seems like a reasonable sort order to me, and relatively explainable.
Sounds reasonable to me as well

> Also, per the standard, we need to return a consistent response, so the response order can't be based on the order that http calls return.
Then we definitely need a consistent way to sort the members array.  I could create some sort of expanded human sort where I group the members array by prefix and then sort within the prefix.  I would assume that the lack of a prefix means that the resource is on the aggregating bmc and should appear first.

I would modify the response's completion handler to:
1. Query D-Bus to retrieve the known prefixes
2. Sort the members array (if it exists) as described above
3. Call the original completion handler

I'd update the completion handler at the start of beginAggregation()

Generally I'm a fan of just inserting in order in this case.  "do action when all things are done" is a really hard concept in bmcweb (and async daemons in general) and involve reference counting and a bunch of other mess, simply making sure that you insert by AlphaNumLess (probably by using std::upper_bound) would shortcut the need for reference counting an destructors.

I think in the other thread we've decided that dbus isn't going to own the prefix definition, so we can skip 1.

step 2 can be replaced by the above "insert in place" operation.
which removes the need to have any step 3

WDYT?

> Generally I'm a fan of just inserting in order in this case.  "do action when all things are done" is a really hard concept in bmcweb (and async daemons in general) and involve reference counting and a bunch of other mess, simply making sure that you insert by AlphaNumLess (probably by using std::upper_bound) would shortcut the need for reference counting an destructors.
> 
> I think in the other thread we've decided that dbus isn't going to own the prefix definition, so we can skip 1.
> 
> step 2 can be replaced by the above "insert in place" operation.
> which removes the need to have any step 3
> 
> WDYT?
I said response in my original reply, but I meant AsyncResp.  I feel like most of those concerns would be covered by waiting to sort until the completion handler of the AsyncResp since that wouldn't get called until all things are done.

However I think your insert in place method is preferable since I wouldn't have to modify the completion handler.  I'll add this change and also assume that:
1. local resources do not have a prefix
2. aggregated resources will contain the prefix "aggregated<#>_" at the start of their resource ID.
Those assumptions align with this thread https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/53797/comments/cbfc9dd5_5c1a8918
